[1]
Date: Thu, 6 Mar 1997 18:09:35 -0800 (PST)
From: Russell McMullen <mcmullen@u.washington.edu>
Because of a thing called the "Feres Doctrine" under which the US
Supreme Court has repeatedly held that the Federal Government is not civily
liable for bad things that happen to active duty service members (since we
cover them under disability procedures.) I believe this also applies to
vendors who supply stuff, like vaccines, armor, airplanes, etc, that meets
DOD (US Dept of Defense) specifications. In other words, no multi-million
dollar settlements for soldiers who get bad reactions to immunizations.
(Dependents and retirees are another question to which I don't pretend
to know the answer.)
As usual, people who need a real legal opinion should get it from a
lawyer, not a pathologist. And if this note bears any resemblance to
official DOD policy, it is purely coincidence.
