[2]
Date: Mon, 10 Mar 1997 14:44:42 -0500
From: Stacey Levitt <levitts@mail.med.upenn.edu>
US military personnel lose their right to sue relating to medical treatment,
among other things, per what is called the 'Feres Doctrine'. It is based on
the concept of 'sovereign immunity'. Previous cases have not fared well
challenging the Feres Doctrine. Therefore, I think few attorneys (and
plaintiffs) would be willing to front the cost of further legal action.
Another important point regards the Federal Vaccine Act.
See:
Daniel A. Cantor, STRIKING A BALANCE BETWEEN PRODUCT
AVAILABILITY AND PRODUCT SAFETY:LESSONS FROM THE VACCINE ACT
The American University, Summer, 1995, 44 Am. U.L. Rev. 1853.
Federal law protects companies that make vaccines, under certain
circumstances, from product liability, because the risks are so
high and, well, we need the vaccines...
--
Stacey Levitt, RN
